      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "All FEA software packages (Ansys Mechanical, FDA in-house solver) operate under documented software quality assurance plans including version control, regression testing, and change management procedures consistent with FDA software lifecycle guidance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Benchmark problems from ASME V&V 10 and internal code verification suites confirm correct implementation of linear elastic constitutive models, contact algorithms, and beam element formulations used in the pedicle screw construct models."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence studies were conducted on all three FEA models. Peak von Mises stress and construct stiffness quantities of interest changed by less than 3% between the penultimate and final mesh refinement levels, confirming adequate spatial discretization."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Linear static analyses were solved using direct sparse solvers with residual norms below 1e-8. No iterative convergence failures were observed across the ensemble runs. Solver tolerances are documented in the simulation reports."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Model setup was independently reviewed by a second analyst at each participating organization. Boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions were verified against the simulation plan prior to execution. No use errors were identified during review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic isotropic material models are appropriate for the titanium alloy components under the quasi-static loading regime of ASTM F1717. Contact between screw and test block is modeled with frictional interfaces consistent with published literature on spinal implant FEA."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, Poisson's ratio) for Ti-6Al-4V ELI were sourced from ASTM F136 and manufacturer certificates of conformance. Geometric dimensions were derived from CMM measurements of physical test specimens with tolerances documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "N=11 physical constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. Sample-to-sample geometric variability was characterized via CMM inspection, and specimen traceability to lot and batch is documented. Sample size is consistent with ASTM F1717 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single load level and displacement rate per ASTM F1717. The absence of multiple test conditions (e.g., varying offset distances or load magnitudes) limits confidence that model predictions generalize beyond the tested configuration. This factor is below the required level and represents a known gap in the validation evidence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs were mapped directly to measured specimen parameters. Geometric fidelity between CAD models and physical specimens was confirmed within manufacturing tolerances. Material property inputs were matched to measured values from the same material lot used in physical testing."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness (N/mm) and peak load at 2% offset yield were compared between FEA ensemble predictions and experimental measurements. All three FEA models predicted stiffness within 8% of experimental mean. Quantitative metrics including normalized error and prediction interval coverage are reported."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and offset yield load are the primary quantities of interest for ASTM F1717 compliance assessment and are directly relevant to the biomechanical performance claims of the pedicle screw system. These quantities are also the basis for regulatory comparison against predicate devices."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the given model risk classification.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the ASTM F1717 test configuration used as the basis for the regulatory submission. The FEA models were validated against the same test standard, loading mode, and construct geometry as the intended regulatory use, providing high relevance of validation evidence to the decision context."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels for a Model Risk Level 3 assessment. The single below-threshold factor (Test conditions, achieved level 2 vs. required level 3) was reviewed by the team and determined to be acceptable given the standardized nature of ASTM F1717 testing, which prescribes a single test configuration. The ensemble approach across three independent FEA implementations provides additional confidence in the simulation predictions. The overall credibility evidence is judged sufficient to support the regulatory decision for this device class.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
